US LEGAL DEFINITION OF MURDER OF A POLICE OFFICER: Whoever, with deliberate and premeditated malice, and with knowledge or reason to know that the victim is a law enforcement officer or public safety employee, kills any law enforcement officer or public safety employee engaged in, or on account of, the performance of such officer’s or employee’s official duties, is guilty of murder of a law enforcement officer or public safety employee, and shall be sentenced to life without the possibility of release. It shall not be a defense to this charge that the victim was acting unlawfully by seizing or attempting to seize the defendant or another person.

US LEGAL DEFINITION OF FIRST DEGREE MURDER:
Any intentional murder that is willful and premeditated with malice aforethought. Felony murder, a charge that may be filed against a defendant who is involved in a dangerous crime where a death results from the crime,[13] is typically first-degree.[14]

Some states also classify killings that occur during the commission of another felony as second-degree murders, although other states characterize these types of killings as murders in the first degree. It's also important to note that an individual can be found guilty of felony murder even if they didn't personally kill anyone.

US LEGAL DEFINITION OF CONSPIRACY TO COMIT MURDER:
If two or more persons conspire to violate section 1111, 1114, 1116, or 1119 of this title, and one or more of such persons do any overt act to effect the object of the conspiracy, each shall be punished by imprisonment for any term of years or for life.

US LEGAL DEFINITION OF CONSPIRACY TO KILL OR KIDNAP: Section 351(d) of Title 18, United States Code, tracks the general conspiracy statute (18 U.S.C. § 371) except that it is limited to the two objects of killing or kidnapping a Member of Congress or other specified person. Section 351(d) does not preclude prosecution under the general conspiracy statute, but merely provides an increased penalty where the object of the conspiracy is to kill or kidnap a person specified in § 351. See United States v. Bazzell, 187 F.2d 878, 885 (7th Cir.), cert. denied, 342 U.S. 849 (1951).

As with the Federal Kidnapping Act (18 U.S.C. § 1201), 18 U.S.C. § 351(b) does not attempt to define the term "kidnap." However, it appears that the essential elements of the offense are the involuntary nature of the seizure and detention. Chatwin v. United States, 326 U.S. 455, 465 (1964). To the extent that transportation is deemed to be an element of kidnapping under this statute, any significant transportation should suffice, cf. 2 Bish. Criminal Law, § 750 (9th Ed.). Analogizing this statute to 18 U.S.C. § 1201(a)(4) (kidnapping of protected foreign officials), it does not appear that transportation across a State line is an element of the offense.
Section 351(b) provides for the death penalty if death results to the victim. The procedures for the imposition of capital punishment are found at 18 U.S.C. §§ 3591 et seq. If the death penalty is applicable, the United States Attorney must comply with the provisions of JM 9-10.000.

US LEGAL DEFINITION OF DESTRUCTION OF GOVERNMENT PROPERTY –OTHER STATUTES AFFECTED: Title 18, United States Code, Section 1362 is a designated "Federal crime of terrorism" if the offense is "calculated to influence or affect the conduct of government by intimidation or coercion, or to retaliate against government conduct . . . ." 18 U.S.C. § 2332b(g)(5). Kind of like none of us want to destroy all insects, but we don't want them in our face/house either so we don't exactly have nice thoughts about them on a regular basis. I think we make the mistake of thinking it is 'wrong' to dislike another group of people and it somehow makes us bad people if we think certain things about those people. What we 'think' isn't the issue, it's what we do.

I had a friend from India when I was in HS and her family did not believe in wearing deodorant. So I had formed a habit of breathing from my mouth around her assuming she would have an unpleasant odor. I have no idea if she did or not b/c my assumption dictated an action that may or may not have been warranted. She didn't know I was doing that so we remained friends. But I could very well have berated myself for thinking "All Indians - from India- smell bad" or I can understand that somewhere this is part of my thought process and choose how I should deal with it that would cause the least amount of harm.

Until we all do that for ourselves and as a race, we will keep lying about how we feel and the result will be, we keep attacking each other b/c we never address the real issues. We sugarcoat, we pretend and we spend more time trying to role play 'nice' than we spend just being kind to one another.

Sadly, none of this will change (well not anytime soon) and each party will have to accept that at some point or the other. Even when dating outside the race: the issues will still be there even if neither party ever addresses it, the world will send reminders every chance it gets. That's just how it is.
